T1  - Venture Capital and Startup Agglomeration
AU  - CHEN, JUN
AU  - EWENS, MICHAEL
Y1  - 2025/08/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13451
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - J Finance
SP  - 2153
EP  - 2198
VL  - 80
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13451
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT This paper examines venture capital's (VC) role in the geographic clustering of high-growth startups. We exploit a rule change that disproportionately impacted U.S. regions that historically lacked VC financing via a restriction of banks to invest in the asset class. A one-standard-deviation increase in VCs' exposure to the rule led to a 20% decline in fund size and a 10% decrease in the likelihood of raising a follow-on fund. Startups were not wholly cushioned: financing and valuations declined. Startups also moved out of impacted states after the rule change, likely exacerbating existing geographic disparity in entrepreneurship.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Is the United States a Lucky Survivor? A Hierarchical Bayesian Approach
AU  - BINSBERGEN, JULES VAN
AU  - HUA, SOPHIA
AU  - PEETERS, JONAS
AU  - WACHTER, JESSICA
Y1  - 2025/08/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13452
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - J Finance
SP  - 2355
EP  - 2388
VL  - 80
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13452
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT Using international data, we quantify the magnitude of survivorship bias in U.S. equity market performance, finding that it explains about one-third of the equity risk premium in the past century. We model the subjective crash belief of an investor who infers the crash risk in the United States by cross-learning from other countries. The U.S. crash probability shows a persistent and widening divergence from the implied global average. We attribute the upward bias in the measured equity premium to crashes that did not occur in-sample and to shocks to valuations resulting from learning about the probability.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Dynamic Banking and the Value of Deposits
AU  - BOLTON, PATRICK
AU  - LI, YE
AU  - WANG, NENG
AU  - YANG, JINQIANG
Y1  - 2025/08/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13454
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - J Finance
SP  - 2063
EP  - 2105
VL  - 80
IS  - 4
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13454
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT We propose a theory of banking in which banks cannot perfectly control deposit flows. Facing uninsurable loan and deposit shocks, banks dynamically manage lending, wholesale funding, deposits, and equity. Deposits create value by lowering funding costs. However, when the bank is undercapitalized and at risk of breaching leverage requirements, the marginal value of deposits can turn negative as deposit inflows, by raising leverage, increase the likelihood of costly equity issuance. Banks' inability to fully control leverage distinguishes them from nondepository intermediaries. Our model suggests a reevaluation of leverage regulations and offers new perspectives on banking in a low-interest-rate environment.
ER  - 

